Generation 3







Bakugan Evolutions is the fourth installment of Bakugan's 2nd Generation. It featured the return of the main casts' original partner Bakugan. The toy line had decided to look back on its history and re-released multiple Bakugan from previous arcs, most of which have an updated design. Evolutions also added the Nanogan, a series of small accessories that call back to the B1 days of the series. The Geogan make a return as well although the Baku-Gear are notably absent. There was even a tie-in with Monster Jam, leading to monster truck toys that resembled Drago.


Due to the saturation of returning Bakugan, there was only a small amount of brand new Bakugan that were introduced. Bakugan Ultra's were also limited to returning Bakugan only, and even then only a handful. New to Evolutions is the Platinum line, where Bakugan would sometimes take on a translucent mold combined with Diecast Metal body parts. Interestingly enough, these tended to be more common than the standard releases. Due to what I assume were financial burdens combined with plans of wrapping up Generation 2, there were far more batches of mixed rarities and outright cancellations on a lot of Bakugan. The chase rarity Bakugan like Diamonds and Elemental-Rares also seemed to be notably more common than they probably should have been.


The dramatically increased variety of Bakugan, combined with a limited window to release them all gave documenting this section a similar vibe to New Vestroia. There were many good ideas and designs here, I only wish it could have been handled with as much grace as the first three series of Generation 2.



Table Legend


Note: The following table does not account for minor paint or hole variations, unless it is an oddity or a very notable difference.


Treatment: A variation from the normal 6 attributed releases. They include translucent plastic, unique color combinations, among other gimmicks.


Core: Standard Bakugan release with no special features.


Ultra: More elaborate version of a Bakugan that resembles its anime counterpart.


Bakugan releases differed by regions of the world and from country to country. For Battle Planet specifically, Takara Tomy handled distribution in Asia. From Armored Alliance and onwards, Spin Master would handle releases almost exclusively. Different regions of the world received waves at different times, and some countries did not receive entire waves at all. Several Bakugan were also unreleased in the USA and Canada.


Note:
Rarity scores are based on how easy the Bakugan is to find for a primarily American buyer, however Sega Toys and Takara Tomy releases have scores based on their own region. This means that if you live outside of the designated region, increase the rarity score by one or two points.


For example, Hydranoid is 6/10 (Moderate) in the US, and did not release in Japan. If you live in Japan, it is likely 8/10 rarity instead.
If a European Bakugan is considered Common (say 3/10), then to an American, consider it Moderate (say 5/10).
This is is because you would have to go out of your way to find sellers or utilize websites or middlemen, and are also likely to have to pay an increased cost in order to obtain it along with international shipping. This effectively raises your barrier to entry, even if the toy in a vacuum is not difficult to find.


- 1/10 - 2/10 (Very Common): Easy to find and relatively cheap, you will likely find a minimum of 10 results upon searching for one online
- 3/10 - 4/10 (Common): Relatively easy to obtain, slightly less numerous and more expensive. Will find a few results in a search
- 5/10 - 6/10 (Moderate): Potentially annoying/expensive to track down, but realistic enough to obtain without too much issue
- 7/10 - 8/10 (Semi-Rare or Rare): One will pop up every few weeks or months. You may have some competition in trying to obtain this
- 9/10 or 10/10 (Very Rare): Realistically, you will not obtain this Bakugan. Get a custom paint job or a recast. Good luck otherwise
- One-Offs: An anomaly that probably shouldn't exist, but has been documented for the sake of completion




List of Returning Bakugan:


Note: Only Bakugan that have a new mold, treatment, or color scheme are listed below.


The following Bakugan were re-released, but are otherwise identical to their original releases and are not listed: Fangzor x Mantonoid, Hydorous x Batrix, Trox x Nobilious, Ferascal, Crackanoid, Jettra, and Demorc. These Bakugan were included in the Evolutions Unbox and Brawl Pack, or the Evolutions Baku-Tin.


The following Mythic Bakugan were intended to be released, but were moved to Bakugan Legends instead: Aquos Dragonoid, Aurelus Pegatrix, Pyrus Trox, Aquos Fade Ninja, Haos Skorporos, Ventus Mantonoid, Darkus Fangzor, Darkus Serpenteze, Pyrus Trhyno, and Elemental Darkus Nillious.
